"Great idea @aminnj! I'm also a big fan and user of profile plots. They are terrific when \"poking\" the data and for figuring out trends, tails in the projections on certain axes (variables), you name it. A big +1 from me on the idea.\n\nThis is a Mean / WeightedMean storage histogram, right? Though making a Profile from an existing histogram would be new.\n\nWe also need to work on better plotting support for Profiles, the information is present in the PlottableHistogram Protocol (`h.kind` returns `\"MEAN\"`), but I don't think we do much with it yet, like customize the plot.\n\n`h.profile(*axis: str | int) -> Histogram[Mean | WeightedMean]` (pretending we had Generic histograms in the typing there, which we don't yet) would be nice, I think; you could give an int axis number or a string axis name, just like project.\r\n\r\nEdit: I think you would just require N-1 axis.\n\nSimplification:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nnum = np.matmul(values, centers)\r\n# Can be written with the matmul operator:\r\nnum = values @ centers\r\n# But, better yet, use tensordot explicitly and remove the silly .T stuff:\r\nnum = np.tensordot(values, centers, [[axis], [0]])\r\n```\r\n\r\nI would like to flip the definition of axis, I'd like to list the axis to profile over, rather than the \"remaining\" axis, because that generalizes far better to ND. (I think I've used that in my tensordot definition already; it also removes all the `.T`'s above)."